ecking across instruments with differing beam patterns.[3]\n\n- CHIME/FRB with outriggers and wide-field follow-up\n  - In extended campaigns, CHIME/FRB detections have been combined with very long baseline interferometry (VLBI) and high-precision localizers (outriggers) to refine positions and test co-detection claims, using the same DM and time-offset formalism as above, plus explicit false-alarm probability calculations and trial corrections.[2][3]\n\n- A multi-telescope FRB 121102 campaign (VLA, Arecibo, Effelsberg, LWA1, AMI-LA)\n  - This historic campaign demonstrated the first subarcsecond localization of an FRB (VLA) with simultaneous detections by other facilities (Arecibo, Effelsberg, LWA1, AMI-LA). They report simultaneous detections across frequencies (1.2–3.5 GHz) and show that some bursts are detected by multiple instruments while others are not, highlighting the importance of cross-instrument DM, timing, and localization consistency for establishing a common origin. This work explicitly discusses cross-telescope simultaneity and multi-frequency behavior as a cornerstone of robust co-detection claims.[11]\n\n- FRB 20180916B simultaneous multi-wavelength campaign\n  - A coordinated campaign tracked FRB 20180916B with radio stations (SRT, uGMRT) and optical/X-ray facilities, providing simultaneous detections and stringent upper limits in non-radio bands. While not all bursts have counterparts in all bands, the setup illustrates the broader validation approach: co-detection requires consistent timing and localization logic across instruments with different modalities.[7]\n\n- FRB follow-up for magnetar-related bursts (SGR 1935+2154)\n  - The contemporaneous radio bursts from the Galactic magnetar SGR 1935+2154 were observed by CHIME, STARE2, and other radio facilities, with DM-like signatures (though in a Galactic context), precise timing, and cross-instrument confirmation demonstrating the viability of multi-instrument validation even in a single-source, high-precision event. This case provides a template for combining DM-like dispersion, time alignment, and sky localization in a localized environment.[8]\n\n3) Statistical formalism and practical considerations\n- Likelihood and Poisson-based coincidence\n  - The standard approach treats the occurrence of a burst in a given time-DM-sky window as a Poisson process. The joint probability of seeing a burst by two instruments within their respective windows, given the all-sky rate and the window sizes, yields a false-alarm probability. The smaller the windows and the lower the background rate, the stronger the claim of a true coincidence. Later FRB verification guidelines explicitly recommend reporting the joint probability and accounting for search/configuration trials.[10][12]\n\n- Data products and verification criteria\n  - Proposals and guidelines emphasize the availability of high-fidelity dynamic spectra, raw voltage or pre-detection data, and complete metadata (exact times, pointings, beam configurations, and calibration logs) to enable independent verification of a candidate co-detection. These practices help separate astrophysical signals from RFI or instrument artifacts and facilitate rigorous cross-instrument validation.[12][10]\n\n4) Quick illustrations and takeaways\n- DM agreement and timing alignment are the backbone: consistent DMs across instruments and corrected arrival times that agree within uncertainties strongly support a shared astrophysical event rather than two unrelated bursts.[1][12]\n- Sky position must overlap between precise and wide-field localizations: sub-arcsecond localization from interferometers overlapping with the other instrument’s error region solidifies the co-detection claim.[11][2]\n- False-alarm probability must be explicit: a quantified joint probability that an unrelated burst would coincide in DM, time, and sky is essential to defend against chance coincidences, especially in crowded or high-rate survey regimes.[10][3]\n\n5) Summary example workflow in practice\n- Step 1: For each instrument, report DM with uncertainties, reference time system, and calibration notes. Check DM agreement within combined uncertainties.[12]\n- Step 2: Convert arrival times to a common reference frequency using the measured DMs, compute residual time differences, and compare to the geometric light-travel delay between sites, including baseline uncertainties.[1]\n- Step 3: Compare localization footprints; require overlap between the high-precision interferometric position and the wide-field localization, with a clear statement of systematic uncertainties.[2]\n- Step 4: Compute a joint false-alarm probability, incorporating the FRB rate, the DM search range, the temporal window, and the sky-area overlap; declare a detection as robust if this probability is below the pre-defined threshold (commonly <1%).[3]\n\nNotes on sources and examples\n- Foundational multi-telescope FRB campaigns and verification guidelines discuss simultaneous detections, DM and timing coherence, and the necessity of explicit false-alarm analysis. For foundational criteria and the 2016 FRB 121102 multi-telescope campaign, see the multi-observatory paper detailing simultaneous detections and frequency coverage across VLA and Arecibo and other instruments.[11]\n- Formal FRB verification guidelines from 2018 onward emphasize comprehensive dynamic spectra, instrument metadata, and criteria for ruling out terrestrial origins, with proposed scoring for similarity and terrestrial concerns, along with practical data products to enable independent verification.[12]\n- The magnetar-related FRB-like bursts and concurrent campaigns (e.g., SGR 1935+2154, CHIME/STARE2) provide concrete context for cross-instrument timing and the interpretation of fast, bright bursts within a Galactic magnetar framework.[8]\n\nCitations\n- Face-to-face cross-instrument timing and DM consistency are standard practice in multi-telescope FRB analyses and are discussed in joint campaigns and verification guidelines.[12]\n- The first sub-arcsecond FRB localization via VLA with concurrent detections by other telescopes demonstrates the importance of sky-position overlap for co-detections.[11]\n- Multi-wavelength follow-up campaigns illustrate the broader verification approach beyond radio-only coincidences, including timing alignment and upper limits across bands.[7][8]\n- The statistical formalism for chance coincidences combines Poisson-rate reasoning with windowed DM/time/sky searches, emphasizing explicit false-alarm probability reporting.[10][3]\n\nIf you’d like, I can tailor these criteria into a checklist you can apply to a specific FRB event (e.g., CHIME/FRB 2020 or CHIME/FRB 20190120B) and provide a concise template for reporting a robust co-detection with exact equations and example numbers.",
