ce apparent sub-ms offset differences even for a truly simultaneous event, undermining the claimed coincidence unless clearly documented and reproduced [see reviews and case studies on FRB timing and dispersion handling; e.g., early interferometric FRB work and subsequent multi-telescope campaigns].[4][5]\n\n- Intra-channel smearing and bandwidth effects\n  - Finite channel bandwidth causes residual intra-channel dispersive smearing, which broadens the observable pulse and can mimic timing offsets between instruments with different channelizations. The problem worsens for high-DM events or for low-frequency observations where dispersion delays are large. Proper accounting requires consistent dedispersion strategies and, ideally, matching or reconcilable effective time resolutions across instruments. If not accounted for, these effects can degrade the inferred simultaneity and inflate false-association claims [discussions of channelization effects and their impact on timing in FRB/interferometric studies].[5][4]\n\n- Reported coincidences vs. chance coincidences\n  - Some claimed multi-telescope coincidences have later been reinterpreted as chance alignments, due to insufficient temporal/spatial coincidence criteria or underestimated false-alarm rates. Re-analyses may involve re-computing the joint false-alarm probability under realistic noise and RFI models, or showing that the number of expected coincidences by chance over the observing window matches or exceeds the observed count. This is a known pitfall in the FRB field, where multiple “simultaneous” detections across facilities were not robust upon closer statistical scrutiny [examples and discussions of retractions and challenging multi-telescope associations are present in the literature].[5]\n\n- False-alarm rate computation and acceptable thresholds\n  - False-alarm rates for multi-telescope associations are typically estimated via (i) empirical measurements of background coincidences (time-slid analyses, off-source trials), (ii) modeling of RFI and noise in each instrument, and (iii) simulations injecting synthetic FRBs to test recovery and coincidence statistics. The acceptable probability depends on the field’s standards and the strength of the claim; sometimes a few parts in 10^3 to 10^5 level of chance coincidence is sought for a robust multi-instrument detection, but there is no universal universal threshold. In practice, claims have been strengthened by: (a) precise localization from interferometry, (b) consistent DM and spectral properties across instruments, and (c) corroborating multi-wavelength or multi-messenger context when available. There are documented debates about what constitutes a convincing association in FRB literature [typical practice and debates are discussed in reviews and methodological papers; see multi-telescope campaigns and VERifications discussions].[4][5]\n\n- Criticisms in the literature\n  - Critics have stressed that association claims must discipline their statistical methodology, reporting of search windows, and treatment of non-detections across bands. Some analyses emphasize that not all coincidences imply a common origin and highlight the danger of selection biases (e.g., publishing sensational simultaneous detections while underreporting null results). Reviews and commentary in the field call for transparent reporting of timing benchmarks, detailed instrument-specific uncertainties, and the use of standardized metrics for significance and false-alarm rates in FRB coincidence studies [Verifying and reporting FRBs; multi-telescope campaigns; methodological discussions].[5]\n\n- Notable lessons from retractions and debates\n  - Early FRB coincidences across facilities showed the importance of careful timing calibration, uniform DM handling, and robust statistical testing. Several cases have illustrated that without rigorous joint timing solutions and explicit false-alarm-rate calculations, apparent simultaneity can be misleading. Subsequent studies emphasize documenting all steps to reproduce timing, DM, and coincidence analyses and encourage independent re-analyses to validate claimed associations [classic and contemporary discussions in the FRB literature].[3][5]\n\nIllustrative guidance for a robust multi-observatory claim\n\n- Timing\n  - Establish and publish a joint timing budget: clock reference (GPS/maser), instrumental delay calibrations, path delays, and end-to-end latency budgets. Report absolute timing uncertainties and cross-check with known, simultaneous calibrator signals if possible. Ensure all time stamps are transferred to a common absolute frame (e.g., TDB or UTC with explicit offsets) and that any barycentering or topocentric corrections are consistently applied.\n\n- Dispersion and alignment\n  - Use a single, explicitly stated dispersion convention for all instruments, or transform measurements to a common convention and clearly show the transformation. Report DM values, reference frequencies, and the exact dedispersion procedure used per instrument, including channelization and residual smearing estimates.\n\n- Statistics\n  - Quantify the false-alarm probability with time-shifted trials and by modeling the joint noise behavior. Present the p-value or Bayes factor for the association, including uncertainties from DM, timing, and channelization. If possible, use independent methods (e.g., different dedispersion pipelines) to verify the result.\n\n- Validation and transparency\n  - Prefer joint localization (e.g., interferometric positions) to boost association credibility. Publish all relevant data products (time-tagged event lists, dedispersion parameters, and calibration metadata) to enable independent replication and reanalysis.\n\nIllustrative example (high-level)\n- A hypothetical two-telescope claim would present: (1) sub-ms timing uncertainty budgets for both telescopes, (2) a common DM value and a demonstrable, consistent arrival time after applying their respective dedispersions, (3) a quantified joint false-alarm probability using time-slid and randomized tests, (4) an interferometric localization to show a common sky position within error bars, and (5) a clear discussion of any prior non-detections in other bands to contextualize the event.\n\nIf you want, I can:\n- Pull together a concise checklist you can apply to a specific FRB pair or event paper to evaluate whether the multi-observatory claim stands up to scrutiny.\n- Summarize the known retractions or controversial cases with citations to the original publications and follow-up analyses.",
